Try using `keydown` in a JavaScript event listener. This will fire every time any key is pressed. [More information on the event.](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Document/keydown_event) In your case, you&#39;re going to want to use this with `event.keyCode` (just like you&#39;re doing now.) You can do this:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    document.addEventListener(&quot;keydown&quot;, e =&gt; {
      var key = e.keyCode;
      console.log(key);
    });

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

As you can see, every time a key is pressed (you might have to click on the window first) the key code will get logged to the console! You can just delete the `console.log` statement and replace that with your own code to parse the result.

Also, the `e =&gt; {/*code*/}` you see is an ES6 short version of a function written like `function(e) {/*code*/}`;

````onkeypress```` can be helpful when creating responsive websites. It allows you to run certain JavaScript upon clicking the affected object. ````onkeypress```` can be used with both HTML and JavaScript. It is up to you to decide which one works best for you.

HTML ````onkeypress```` can be created with a JavaScript function:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; onkeypress=&quot;myFunction();&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
        function myFunction() {
            alert(&quot;I am in a function!&quot;);
        }
    &lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

HTML ````onpkeypress```` can also be triggered with JavaScript directly:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; onkeypress=&quot;alert(&#39;I am in direct HTML!&#39;);&quot; /&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

HTML ````onkeypress```` can be used with *any* element.

````onkeypress```` can be activated with JavaScript as well.

JavaScript ````onkeypress```` can be activated directly:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; id=&quot;selector&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
        document.getElementById(&quot;selector&quot;).onkeypress = function() {myFunction()};
        function myFunction() {
            document.getElementById(&quot;selector&quot;).style.backgroundColor = &quot;red&quot;;
        }
    &lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

JavaScript ````onkeypress```` can also be activated with addEventListener():

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; id=&quot;selector&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
        document.getElementById(&quot;selector&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;keypress&quot;, myFunction);
        function myFunction() {
            document.getElementById(&quot;selector&quot;).style.backgroundColor = &quot;red&quot;;
        }
    &lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can use ````event.keyCode```` to specify which key is pressed:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; id=&quot;selector&quot; onkeypress=&quot;myFunction(event);&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;script&gt;
        function myFunction(event) {
            var x = event.keyCode;
            if (x == 27) {
                alert(&quot;Escape key pressed!&quot;);
            }
        }
    &lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

[Keycodes][1]

[Mozilla Documentation][2]


  [1]: https://keycode.info
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/GlobalEventHandlers/onkeypress

